> As such, it must also be the case that draining the socket on entry to `pldm_transport_mctp_demux_recv()` is enough

Ugh, that was meant to be `pldm_transport_mctp_demux_send()`.

But thinking about that some more, `pldm_transport_send_recv()` is only useful for requests, while the the transport-specific send and recv callbacks shouldn't care about whether they're sending or receiving requests or responses.

So maybe the draining should be done in `pldm_transport_send_recv()`, contrary to the first point in my previous comment. It will just never be the case that if the AF_MCTP transport is in use that anything needs to be drained. We can test whether or not anything needs to be drained using the `pldm_transport_poll()`. Something like:

```
for (int i = 0; i <= PLDM_TID_MAX && pldm_transport_poll(transport, 0) == 1; i++) {
    pldm_transport_recv_msg(...);
    /* Discard the message */
}
```

A) That is just my example which the second GetPDRs command is sent by pldmtool after 32 GetSensorReading of pldmd. But it can be more than 32 GetSensorReading responses. It depends on:
1. How long does it take to finish one GetSensorReading commands?
2. How long does GetInstanceID method of D-Bus take to response new InstanceId for pldmtool?
3. How fast the pldmd reads the sensors?

Maybe 
```
for (int i = 0; i <= (32 * 256) && pldm_transport_poll(transport, 0) == 1; i++) {
    pldm_transport_recv_msg(...);
    /* Discard the message */
}
```
can make sure all existing responses will be freed (I don't think we can have 32 * 256 response messages)  but if `polling is not supported` then the above `for` will always run 32 * 256 times.
```
	/* If polling isn't supported then always indicate the transport is ready */
	if (!transport->init_pollfd) {
		return 1;
	}
```


B) With current implementation, I'm assuming that there is some point which pldm_transport_send_recv_msg will polls all of existing messages.
But this assumption can be incorrect if `polling isn't supported`.

In that case, we need some way to checking there is no response using pldm_transport_recv_msg().


C) Can you think again about original solution 'add checking type/command' after those discussion?
+ It is simple.
+ No definite case because we have time out 4800ms
+ If we use above solutions , when we polling the existing response before sending request more response from pldmd can come -> take more time.

So the final question is which solution will we choose? 
```
for (int i = 0; i <= 8196 && pldm_transport_poll(transport, 0) == 1; i++) {
    pldm_transport_recv_msg(...);
    /* Discard the message */
}
```

or 
```
do
{
    pldm_transport_recv_msg(...);
    /* Discard the message */
}
while (pldm_transport_poll(transport, 0) == 1);
```
IMO, there is the point which `pldm_transport_poll(transport, 0)` will return 0 (time out) so both codes will be exited at some points (no infinity loop).
Because there is no guarantee that there are only 8196 messages which are not consumed by pldmtool so I think `do while` is the good way to go.
